Algebra & Number Systems

Quadratic Formula

x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}

This is the universal solution to the general quadratic equation ax^2+bx+c=0 ( a\neq 0 ). The term under the square‑root, \Delta = b^2-4ac, is called the discriminant. Three cases arise:

· \Delta > 0: two distinct real roots.
· \Delta = 0: exactly one real root (a repeated root, sometimes called a “double root”).
· \Delta < 0: two complex‑conjugate roots.

Historically, the Indian mathematician Brahmagupta (628 CE) stated the first explicit (though not yet fully general) solution that included negative numbers. Al‑Khwarizmi (c. 820 CE) later classified six types of quadratics (his work lacked negative numbers and zero) and gave systematic methods for solving them. The modern symbolic formula coalesced during the Islamic Golden Age.

Binomial Theorem

(x+y)^n = \sum_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{k}x^{n-k}y^k ,\qquad
\binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}

The binomial coefficient \binom{n}{k} counts the number of ways to choose k unordered elements from a set of n elements. Early combinatorial knowledge appears in Pingala’s Chandaḥśāstra (c. 200 BCE), which contains a method for computing binomial coefficients. Isaac Newton (1665) generalized the theorem to real exponents, writing the expansion as an infinite series.

Euler’s Identity

e^{i\pi} + 1 = 0

Often called “the most beautiful formula in mathematics,” it unites five fundamental constants: e (the base of natural logarithms), i (the imaginary unit), \pi (the circle constant), 1, and 0. It is the special case \theta=\pi of Euler’s formula e^{i\theta}=\cos\theta+i\sin\theta. The identity is central to complex analysis, AC circuit theory (Steinmetz phasors), Fourier transforms, and quantum‑mechanical plane‑wave formalisms.

Euler’s Formula (Complex Exponential)

e^{i\theta} = \cos\theta + i\sin\theta

This bridge between exponential and trigonometric functions was published by Euler in 1748. It enables the representation of sinusoidal signals as complex exponentials, which drastically simplifies the analysis of AC circuits, Fourier transforms, and quantum‑mechanical wavefunctions.

Logarithm Product Rule

\log_b(xy) = \log_b x + \log_b y

The logarithm converts multiplication into addition. John Napier published the first table of logarithms in 1614, a breakthrough that Laplace praised as “doubling the life of the astronomer.” The natural logarithm can be defined as an integral: \ln x = \int_1^x dt/t.

Sums of Powers

\sum_{k=1}^n k = \frac{n(n+1)}{2},\qquad
\sum_{k=1}^n k^2 = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}

The first formula is associated with a story about Gauss (age 7) who instantly summed the integers from 1 to 100. Archimedes derived the formula for \sum k^2. Jakob Bernoulli (1713) discovered the general power‑sum formula using what are now called Bernoulli numbers, which appear throughout number theory and analysis.

Arithmetic and Geometric Series

S_n = \frac{n}{2}(a_1+a_n),\qquad
S_\infty = \frac{a}{1-r}\quad (|r|<1)

The arithmetic series formula gives the sum of n equally spaced terms. The geometric series converges to a finite limit when the common ratio satisfies |r|<1. Euclid studied geometric progressions, and Archimedes used infinite geometric series to resolve Zeno’s dichotomy paradox ( \sum_{k=1}^\infty d/2^k = d ).

AM–GM Inequality

\frac{a_1+\cdots+a_n}{n} \ge \sqrt[n]{a_1\cdots a_n} \ge \frac{n}{\sum 1/a_i}

The arithmetic mean is always at least the geometric mean, which in turn is at least the harmonic mean. Equality holds iff all a_i are equal. Cauchy (1821) proved the general version via forward‑backward induction. The inequality is foundational to the maximum‑entropy principle, geometric programming, and isoperimetric inequalities.

Cauchy–Schwarz Inequality

\left(\sum a_i b_i\right)^2 \le \left(\sum a_i^2\right)\!\left(\sum b_i^2\right)

In an inner‑product space: |\langle u,v\rangle| \le \|u\|\cdot\|v\|. Cauchy gave the sum form (1821); Schwarz extended it to integrals (1885). It implies the Heisenberg uncertainty principle and the bound |\rho|\le 1 for correlation coefficients.

Cubic Equation (Cardano’s Formula)

x^3+px+q=0,\qquad
x = \sqrt[3]{-\frac{q}{2}+\sqrt{\Delta}} + \sqrt[3]{-\frac{q}{2}-\sqrt{\Delta}},\quad
\Delta = \frac{q^2}{4} + \frac{p^3}{27}

del Ferro first solved the depressed cubic around 1515; Tartaglia rediscovered it in 1535, and Cardano published it in the Ars Magna (1545), breaking a sacred oath. When \Delta<0 (the casus irreducibilis), the formula yields real roots that appear in complex form—a puzzle that spurred the acceptance of complex numbers.

Viète’s Formulas (General Polynomial)

\sum z_i = -\frac{a_{n-1}}{a_n},\qquad
\prod z_i = (-1)^n\frac{a_0}{a_n}

François Viète (1591) discovered that symmetric functions of the roots can be expressed in terms of the coefficients. These relations are intimately tied to Gauss’s Fundamental Theorem of Algebra (PhD dissertation, 1799): every non‑constant polynomial with complex coefficients has at least one complex root.

Multinomial Theorem

(x_1+\cdots+x_m)^n = \sum_{k_1+\cdots+k_m=n} \frac{n!}{k_1!\cdots k_m!} x_1^{k_1}\cdots x_m^{k_m}

Leibniz (1676) formulated this generalization of the binomial theorem. The multinomial coefficient counts the number of ways of partitioning n distinct items into m groups of sizes k_1,\dots,k_m. It is essential in statistical mechanics for counting microstates and underlies the multinomial distribution.

Complex Conjugate Properties

\overline{z_1+z_2}=\overline{z_1}+\overline{z_2},\qquad
\overline{z_1 z_2}=\overline{z_1}\cdot\overline{z_2}

Conjugation distributes over addition and multiplication. The modulus |z|=\sqrt{z\overline{z}} gives the Euclidean distance from the origin in the complex plane. Real polynomials have real coefficients precisely when complex roots appear in conjugate pairs.

De Moivre’s Theorem

(\cos\theta + i\sin\theta)^n = \cos(n\theta) + i\sin(n\theta)

Published by Abraham de Moivre in 1707, the theorem allows one to derive multiple‑angle identities from the binomial expansion of the right‑hand side. It is a direct consequence of Euler’s formula: (e^{i\theta})^n = e^{in\theta}.

Roots of Unity

\zeta_n^k = e^{2\pi i k/n},\qquad
\prod_{k=1}^{n-1}(1-\zeta_n^k)=n

The n‑th roots of unity form a cyclic group of order n under multiplication. Their sum is zero: \sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\zeta_n^k=0. They are the “twiddle factors” in the Fast Fourier Transform and underlie the factorization of cyclotomic polynomials.

Polynomial Remainder & Factor Theorem

P(x)=Q(x)(x-a)+P(a),\qquad
P(a)=0 \iff (x-a)\mid P(x)

The Remainder Theorem: evaluating a polynomial P(x) at x=a yields the remainder upon division by (x-a). The Factor Theorem: a is a root if and only if (x-a) is a factor. These are the basis of synthetic division (Horner’s method).

Vieta for Cubic

x^3+px^2+qx+r=0,\quad \sum r_i = -p,\quad \sum_{i<j} r_i r_j = q,\quad r_1 r_2 r_3 = -r

A specialization of Viète’s formulas to the cubic degree: the sum of roots equals -p; the sum of pair‑wise products equals q; the product equals -r.

Rational Root Test

\frac{p}{q} \text{ is a root of } a_n x^n+\cdots+a_0 \;\Longrightarrow\; p\mid a_0,\; q\mid a_n

Any rational root of an integer‑coefficient polynomial has its numerator dividing the constant term and its denominator dividing the leading coefficient. This drastically reduces the search for rational roots.

Descartes’ Rule of Signs

\#\text{ positive real roots} \le \#\text{ sign changes in coefficients}

The actual number of positive real roots differs from the bound by an even integer. Applying the rule to P(-x) bounds the number of negative roots.

Partial Fractions

\frac{P(x)}{\prod (x-r_i)^{e_i}} = \sum_i \sum_{j=1}^{e_i} \frac{A_{ij}}{(x-r_i)^j}

Every rational function can be decomposed into a sum of simpler fractions with denominators that are powers of linear (or irreducible quadratic) factors. The decomposition is essential for integrating rational functions and for computing inverse Laplace transforms in control theory.

Arithmetic Mean

\bar{x} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i

Among all possible constants c, the arithmetic mean minimizes the sum of squared deviations: \sum (x_i-c)^2. This is a consequence of Gauss’s least‑squares principle.

Finite Geometric Series

\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} ar^k = a\frac{1-r^n}{1-r},\qquad r\neq 1

When |r|<1, letting n\to\infty yields the infinite geometric series \sum_{0}^\infty ar^k = a/(1-r). The formula appears in Z‑transforms, mortgage calculations, and everywhere else that geometric growth is discounted.

Telescoping Series

\sum_{k=1}^n (a_k - a_{k+1}) = a_1 - a_{n+1}

Intermediate terms cancel in successive pairs. Many series can be recast as telescoping sums via partial fractions—for example, \sum 1/(k(k+1)) = 1.

Absolute Value

|x| = \begin{cases} x & x\ge 0 \\ -x & x<0 \end{cases},\qquad
|x+y|\le |x|+|y|

The absolute value is a norm on \mathbb{R}; the triangle inequality is its defining property. It generalizes to the metric |x-a| measuring distance between real numbers.

Floor & Ceiling

\lfloor x\rfloor = \max\{n\in\mathbb{Z}: n\le x\},\qquad
\lceil x\rceil = \min\{n\in\mathbb{Z}: n\ge x\}

Floor maps a real number to the greatest integer less than or equal to it; ceiling to the least integer greater than or equal to it. These functions are ubiquitous in computer science for integer division, array indexing, and complexity analysis.

Conjugate Prior (Bayesian Statistics)

P(\theta \mid x) \propto P(x\mid\theta)\,P(\theta)

A conjugate prior ensures that the posterior distribution belongs to the same family as the prior. Classic pairs include Beta–Binomial, Gamma–Poisson, and Normal–Normal. This property makes sequential Bayesian updating computationally tractable.

Exponential Equation

a^x = b \;\Longrightarrow\; x = \log_a b,\qquad a^{x+y} = a^x a^y

The exponential function a^x is injective for a>0,\;a\neq 1. Exponential laws model population growth (k>0) and radioactive decay (k<0).

