Geometry & Topology

Pythagorean Theorem

a^2 + b^2 = c^2

The oldest evidence appears on the Babylonian tablet Plimpton 322 (c. 1800 BCE), which lists Pythagorean triples. Euclid’s Elements I.47 gives a classic geometric proof; over 370 distinct proofs are known today.

Law of Cosines

c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab\cos C

Jamshīd al‑Kāshī (1427) provided the first explicit statement suitable for triangulation; in French the law is called Théorème d’Al‑Kashi. Setting C=90^\circ recovers the Pythagorean theorem. The law is fundamental to GPS trilateration.

Heron’s Formula

A = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)},\quad s = \frac{a+b+c}{2}

Heron of Alexandria (c. 60 CE) gave this formula for the area of a triangle in terms of its side lengths. Qin Jiushao (1247) independently discovered it in China, and Brahmagupta later generalized it to cyclic quadrilaterals.

Circle Area & Circumference

A = \pi r^2,\qquad C = 2\pi r

Archimedes (c. 250 BCE) used the method of exhaustion to bound the area. Zu Chongzhi (480 CE) computed \pi to seven decimal places. Lindemann (1882) proved that \pi is transcendental, settling the ancient problem of “squaring the circle.”

Sphere Volume & Surface Area

V = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3,\qquad A = 4\pi r^2

Archimedes discovered that a sphere has two‑thirds the volume of its circumscribing cylinder; he asked that this ratio be carved on his tombstone. Cicero later rediscovered the overgrown tomb in Sicily.

Euler Characteristic (Polyhedra)

V - E + F = 2

Euler (1758) showed that for any convex polyhedron, vertices minus edges plus faces equals 2. For a surface of genus g, the formula generalizes to V - E + F = 2 - 2g. Poincaré (1895) extended it to the Euler characteristic \chi = \sum (-1)^i b_i.

Ellipse Area & Perimeter

A = \pi ab,\qquad C \approx \pi(a+b)\left(1 + \frac{3h}{10+\sqrt{4-3h}}\right)

Apollonius (c. 200 BCE) wrote the foundational treatise Conics. Kepler (1609) found that planetary orbits are ellipses. The perimeter has no elementary closed form; Ramanujan (1914) gave the highly accurate approximation shown above.

Great‑Circle Distance

d = R\arccos\!\bigl(\sin\phi_1\sin\phi_2 + \cos\phi_1\cos\phi_2\cos(\Delta\lambda)\bigr)

Hipparchus (c. 150 BCE) founded spherical trigonometry. The formula gives the shortest path between two points on a sphere. The haversine variant is numerically stable for modern GPS navigation.

Gauss–Bonnet Theorem

\int_M K\,dA = 2\pi\,\chi(M)

Gauss’s Theorema Egregium (1827) showed that Gaussian curvature K is intrinsic to the surface. The theorem bridges local geometry (curvature) with global topology (Euler characteristic).

Triangle Area (Base‑Height & Sine Form)

A = \frac12 bh = \frac12 ab\sin C

The fundamental area formula generalizes: base × height / 2, or half the product of two sides and the sine of the included angle.

Parallelogram Area

A = bh = |\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}|

Area equals base times height, which also equals the magnitude of the cross product of two adjacent side vectors.

Trapezoid Area

A = \frac{a+b}{2}h

The average of the parallel sides times the height. Simpson’s rule for numerical integration reduces to this formula when n=1.

Regular Polygon Area

A = \frac14 n s^2 \cot(\pi/n)

As n\to\infty, the area approaches \pi r^2.

Circular Sector

A = \frac12 r^2\theta,\qquad s = r\theta\quad (\theta\text{ in radians})

Setting \theta=2\pi recovers the full circle area and circumference.

Spherical Cap

V = \frac{\pi h^2}{3}(3r-h),\qquad A = 2\pi rh

For h=2r (the full sphere), the formulas reduce to the familiar V=4\pi r^3/3 and A=4\pi r^2.

Cone Volume

V = \frac13 \pi r^2 h

The volume of a right circular cone is exactly one‑third that of the circumscribing cylinder. Democritus (c. 400 BCE) first stated this fact; Eudoxus gave a rigorous proof.

Cylinder Volume

V = \pi r^2 h

Base area times height; lateral surface area is 2\pi rh. It is the archetypal example of Cavalieri’s principle.

Tetrahedron Volume

V = \frac16 |(\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b})\cdot\mathbf{c}|

The volume is one‑sixth of the scalar triple product of three edge vectors emanating from a vertex.

Distance from Point to Plane

d = \frac{|ax_0+by_0+cz_0+d|}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}

The numerator is the absolute value of the plane equation evaluated at the point; the denominator is the magnitude of the normal vector.

Angle Between Vectors

\cos\theta = \frac{\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|\|\mathbf{b}\|}

\theta=0^\circ when parallel, 90^\circ when perpendicular, 180^\circ when antiparallel.

Vector Reflection Formula

\mathbf{r} = \mathbf{d} - 2(\mathbf{d}\cdot\mathbf{n})\mathbf{n}

Reflects a direction vector \mathbf{d} across a surface with unit normal \mathbf{n}. Fundamental to ray tracing, optics (law of reflection), and billiard dynamics.

Polyhedron Volume (Divergence‑Theorem Form)

V = \frac13 \sum_{\text{faces}} (\mathbf{c}_f\cdot\mathbf{n}_f)A_f

Volume can be computed via the divergence theorem as one‑third of the sum over faces of (centroid · normal) × area.

Curvature of a Space Curve

\kappa = \frac{|\mathbf{r}'\times\mathbf{r}''|}{|\mathbf{r}'|^3}

For a circle of radius R, \kappa = 1/R. The osculating circle (best‑fitting circle) has radius 1/\kappa.

Torsion of a Space Curve

\tau = \frac{(\mathbf{r}'\times\mathbf{r}'')\cdot\mathbf{r}'''}{|\mathbf{r}'\times\mathbf{r}''|^2}

Torsion measures how sharply a curve twists out of its osculating plane. A planar curve has \tau=0. Together with curvature \kappa, the Frenet‑Serret frame is fully specified.

Surface Area of Revolution

A = 2\pi\int_a^b f(x)\sqrt{1+[f'(x)]^2}\,dx

Area generated by rotating y=f(x) about the x-axis, derived from the frustum lateral area element dA = 2\pi y\,ds.

Volume of Revolution (Disk Method)

V = \pi\int_a^b [f(x)]^2\,dx

Volume generated by rotating y=f(x) about the x-axis. For rotation about the y-axis, cylindrical shells yield V = 2\pi\int x f(x)\,dx.

Spherical Coordinates

\begin{aligned}
x &= r\sin\phi\cos\theta,\\
y &= r\sin\phi\sin\theta,\\
z &= r\cos\phi,\\
dV &= r^2\sin\phi\,dr\,d\phi\,d\theta
\end{aligned}

The Jacobian r^2\sin\phi is the local volume scale factor. These coordinates are ideal for integrating over spheres and for central‑potential problems in quantum mechanics.

Cylindrical Coordinates

x = r\cos\theta,\quad y = r\sin\theta,\quad z = z,\quad dV = r\,dr\,d\theta\,dz

Jacobian = r. Used for problems with axial symmetry: fluid flow in pipes, magnetic fields around wires.

Shoelace Formula

A = \frac12\left|\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i y_{i+1} - x_{i+1}y_i)\right|

Gives the area of a simple polygon from its vertex coordinates, in O(n) time. The name comes from the criss‑cross pattern reminiscent of lacing a shoe.

