Trigonometry & Hyperbolics

Pythagorean Identity

\sin^2\theta + \cos^2\theta = 1

On the unit circle, the coordinates (\cos\theta,\sin\theta) satisfy x^2+y^2=1, so this identity is nothing but the Pythagorean theorem in trigonometric form. All other trig identities ultimately derive from this one.

Sine & Cosine Sum Formulas

\sin(A\pm B) = \sin A\cos B \pm \cos A\sin B

Ptolemy (c. 150 CE) used these in the Almagest to construct trigonometric tables. They enabled all pre‑calculator navigation and astronomy.

Hyperbolic Functions

\sinh x = \frac{e^x - e^{-x}}{2},\qquad
\cosh^2 x - \sinh^2 x = 1

Introduced by Riccati (1757), these functions parametrize the hyperbola x^2-y^2=1. They appear in Lorentz boosts of special relativity, the catenary curve, and complex analysis.

Law of Sines

\frac{a}{\sin A} = \frac{b}{\sin B} = \frac{c}{\sin C} = 2R

Al‑Battani (c. 900 CE) used this for astronomical calculations; Al‑Tusi (1250) refined it at the Maragheh observatory. Here R is the circumradius.

Double‑Angle Formulas

\sin 2\theta = 2\sin\theta\cos\theta,\qquad
\cos 2\theta = \cos^2\theta - \sin^2\theta

Direct consequences of the sum formulas with A=B=\theta. Equivalent forms \cos2\theta = 2\cos^2\theta-1 = 1-2\sin^2\theta are used for power reduction.

Half‑Angle Formulas

\sin\frac{\theta}{2} = \sqrt{\frac{1-\cos\theta}{2}},\qquad
\cos\frac{\theta}{2} = \sqrt{\frac{1+\cos\theta}{2}}

Derived from \cos2\alpha = 1-2\sin^2\alpha with \alpha=\theta/2. Essential for the Weierstrass (tangent half‑angle) substitution in rational trig integrals.

Product‑to‑Sum Formula

\sin A\cos B = \frac12\bigl[\sin(A+B) + \sin(A-B)\bigr]

Known historically as prosthaphaeresis (Greek: “addition and subtraction”), this was used by astronomers like Tycho Brahe to multiply large numbers before logarithms were available.

Sum‑to‑Product Formula

\sin A + \sin B = 2\sin\frac{A+B}{2}\cos\frac{A-B}{2}

Used to solve trigonometric equations (e.g., \sin 3x + \sin x = 0) and in beat‑frequency analysis.

Inverse Trig Derivatives

\frac{d}{dx}\arcsin x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}},\qquad
\frac{d}{dx}\arctan x = \frac{1}{1+x^2}

These yield the standard integration formulas \int dx/\sqrt{1-x^2} = \arcsin x + C and \int dx/(1+x^2) = \arctan x + C.

Trigonometric Equations

\sin x = \sin\alpha \;\Longrightarrow\; x = n\pi + (-1)^n\alpha



\cos x = \cos\alpha \;\Longrightarrow\; x = 2n\pi \pm \alpha,\qquad
\tan x = \tan\alpha \;\Longrightarrow\; x = n\pi + \alpha

General solutions exploit periodicity and symmetry.

Secant, Cosecant, Cotangent

\sec x = \frac{1}{\cos x},\quad \csc x = \frac{1}{\sin x},\quad \cot x = \frac{\cos x}{\sin x}

Derivatives: \frac{d}{dx}\sec x = \sec x\tan x, \frac{d}{dx}\csc x = -\csc x\cot x. A classic integral: \int \sec x\,dx = \ln|\sec x + \tan x| + C.

Small‑Angle Approximations

\sin x \approx x,\qquad \cos x \approx 1 - \frac{x^2}{2},\qquad \tan x \approx x

These are the first‑order Taylor expansions for |x|\ll 1 (in radians). They are used in the simple pendulum formula T \approx 2\pi\sqrt{L/g}.

Phase‑Shift Representation

A\sin(\omega t + \phi) = A\cos\phi\sin\omega t + A\sin\phi\cos\omega t

Any sinusoidal signal can be decomposed into sine and cosine components. In AC circuits, this splits voltage into resistive (cos) and reactive (sin) parts.

Spherical Law of Cosines

\cos c = \cos a\cos b + \sin a\sin b\cos C

For a spherical triangle on a unit sphere. It reduces to the planar law of cosines for small triangles and is essential for celestial navigation.

