Single‑Variable Calculus

Definition of the Derivative

f'(x) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}

Newton (1666) and Leibniz (1684) independently invented calculus; Cauchy (1821) and Weierstrass (1861) later placed the concept on a rigorous \varepsilon-\delta foundation.

Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (FTC)

\frac{d}{dx}\int_a^x f(t)\,dt = f(x),\qquad
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a)\quad (F' = f)

Differentiation and integration are inverse operations. James Gregory (1668) and Isaac Barrow (1670, Newton’s teacher) had geometric versions; Newton and Leibniz gave the calculus form we use today.

Gaussian Integral

\int_{-\infty}^\infty e^{-x^2}\,dx = \sqrt{\pi}

First evaluated by de Moivre (1733) in a probability context; Gauss (1809) used it for the normal distribution. The classic proof squares the integral and converts to polar coordinates.

Taylor Series

f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{f^{(n)}(a)}{n!}(x-a)^n

Published by Brook Taylor in 1715. Lagrange (1797) provided an explicit remainder form. Abel (1826) gave a counterexample of a smooth function whose Taylor series converges to the wrong value, showing that smoothness does not imply analyticity.

Gamma Function

\Gamma(z) = \int_0^\infty t^{z-1}e^{-t}\,dt,\qquad \Gamma(1/2)=\sqrt{\pi}

Euler (1729–30, at age 22) generalized the factorial to complex numbers: \Gamma(n+1)=n!. The related Beta function B(x,y)=\Gamma(x)\Gamma(y)/\Gamma(x+y) is fundamental to Bayesian statistics.

Dirichlet (Sinc) Integral

\int_0^\infty \frac{\sin x}{x}\,dx = \frac{\pi}{2}

Dirichlet (1829) showed this integral equals \pi/2 regardless of frequency. In signal processing, it is the impulse response of the ideal low‑pass filter.

Stirling’s Approximation

n! \sim \sqrt{2\pi n}\left(\frac{n}{e}\right)^n

de Moivre (1730) found the n^n e^{-n} part; Stirling (1730) added the \sqrt{2\pi n} factor. For n=10, the approximation is within 1% of the exact value. The log form \ln n! \approx n\ln n - n is the basis of entropy in statistical mechanics.

Product Rule

(fg)' = f'g + fg'

Leibniz (1684) gave this rule. The generalized Leibniz rule for the n-th derivative is (fg)^{(n)} = \sum \binom{n}{k} f^{(n-k)}g^{(k)}.

Quotient Rule

\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)' = \frac{f'g - fg'}{g^2}

Follows from the product rule and chain rule.

Chain Rule

\frac{d}{dx}f(g(x)) = f'(g(x))\,g'(x)

In Leibniz notation: \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{dy}{du}\cdot\frac{du}{dx}. This is the most frequently used differentiation rule.

Implicit Differentiation

\frac{d}{dx}F(x,y)=0 \;\Longrightarrow\; \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{\partial_x F}{\partial_y F}

When y is implicitly defined by F(x,y)=0, differentiate both sides with respect to x and solve for dy/dx. Example: x^2+y^2=1 gives dy/dx = -x/y.

Mean Value Theorem

f'(c) = \frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a},\quad c\in(a,b)

Lagrange (1797) stated that there exists a point where the tangent is parallel to the secant. The special case f(a)=f(b) is Rolle’s theorem.

Intermediate Value Theorem

f \text{ continuous on }[a,b] \;\Longrightarrow\; \forall\,y\in[f(a),f(b)]\; \exists\,c: f(c)=y

Bolzano (1817) proved that a continuous function attains every value between its endpoints.

Extreme Value Theorem

f \text{ continuous on }[a,b] \;\Longrightarrow\; \exists\max f,\; \exists\min f

A continuous function on a closed, bounded interval attains its maximum and minimum. Optimization then reduces to checking critical points (f'=0 or undefined) and endpoints.

Concavity Test

f''(x) > 0 \Rightarrow \text{concave up},\qquad f''(x) < 0 \Rightarrow \text{concave down}

An inflection point occurs where f'' changes sign; f''(x)=0 is necessary but not sufficient (e.g., f(x)=x^4 at x=0).

L’Hôpital’s Rule

\lim\frac{f}{g} = \lim\frac{f'}{g'}\quad (0/0 \text{ or } \infty/\infty)

Discovered by Johann Bernoulli (1694) but published by L’Hôpital. Care must be taken to avoid circular reasoning when applying the rule.

u-Substitution

\int f(g(x))\,g'(x)\,dx = \int f(u)\,du,\quad u=g(x)

The inverse of the chain rule for integration. It is the most fundamental integration technique.

Trigonometric Substitution

x = a\sin\theta,\; a\tan\theta,\; a\sec\theta\quad\text{for}\quad \sqrt{a^2-x^2},\; \sqrt{a^2+x^2},\; \sqrt{x^2-a^2}

The Pythagorean identity transforms the square‑root into an algebraic expression.

Partial Fractions Integration

\int\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}dx = \sum\int\frac{A}{(x-r)^k}dx

Decompose a rational function and integrate term by term.

Improper Integrals

\int_a^\infty f(x)\,dx = \lim_{b\to\infty}\int_a^b f(x)\,dx

Convergence criteria: \int_1^\infty 1/x^p\,dx converges iff p>1; \int_0^1 1/x^p\,dx converges iff p<1.

Arc Length

L = \int_a^b \sqrt{1+[f'(x)]^2}\,dx = \int_a^b |\mathbf{r}'(t)|\,dt

Length is obtained by integrating speed along the curve.

Surface of Revolution Area

A = 2\pi\int_a^b f(x)\sqrt{1+[f'(x)]^2}\,dx

Rotating a curve about the x-axis: circumference at each x times the differential arc length.

Work Integral

W = \int_a^b F(x)\,dx = \int_C \mathbf{F}\cdot d\mathbf{r}

Work is the integral of force along a path. For conservative forces, work equals the change in potential, and the integral is path‑independent if \nabla\times\mathbf{F}=0.

Center of Mass

\bar{x} = \frac{\int x\,dm}{\int dm}

For uniform density, this reduces to \int x\,dA / \int dA for planar regions and \int x\,dV / \int dV for solids.

Moment of Inertia

I = \int r^2\,dm

Rotational inertia resists angular acceleration. The parallel‑axis theorem states I = I_{\text{cm}} + Md^2.

Differential Equation y' = ky

\frac{dy}{dt} = ky \;\Longrightarrow\; y(t) = y_0 e^{kt}

k>0 gives exponential growth (population, compound interest); k<0 gives exponential decay (radioactivity, cooling). The half‑life for decay is t_{1/2} = \ln 2/|k|.

Logistic Equation

\frac{dP}{dt} = rP\left(1-\frac{P}{K}\right),\qquad
P(t) = \frac{K}{1+Ce^{-rt}}

Verhulst (1838) introduced this S‑shaped growth model with carrying capacity K. It describes population dynamics, technology adoption, and epidemiology.

---

Multivariable & Vector Calculus

Gradient

\nabla f = (\partial_x f,\; \partial_y f,\; \partial_z f)

Hamilton (1837) introduced the symbol \nabla (“nabla”). The gradient points in the direction of steepest ascent; gradient descent \theta \leftarrow \theta - \eta\nabla_\theta L is the engine behind modern neural‑network training.

Divergence

\nabla\cdot\mathbf{F} = \partial_x F_x + \partial_y F_y + \partial_z F_z

Divergence measures the source strength of a vector field: \nabla\cdot\mathbf{F}>0 indicates a source, <0 a sink. Maxwell’s equation: \nabla\cdot\mathbf{E} = \rho/\varepsilon_0.

Curl

\nabla\times\mathbf{F} = \begin{vmatrix}
\hat{i} & \hat{j} & \hat{k} \\
\partial_x & \partial_y & \partial_z \\
F_x & F_y & F_z
\end{vmatrix}

Curl measures the local rotation (vorticity) of a vector field. Key identities: \nabla\times(\nabla f)=0, \nabla\cdot(\nabla\times\mathbf{F})=0. Faraday’s law: \nabla\times\mathbf{E} = -\partial\mathbf{B}/\partial t.

Divergence Theorem (Gauss–Ostrogradsky)

\iint_{\partial V}\mathbf{F}\cdot d\mathbf{S} = \iiint_V (\nabla\cdot\mathbf{F})\,dV

Gauss (1813) and Ostrogradsky (1826) established this result independently. It equates the flux through a closed surface to the volume integral of the divergence.

Stokes’ Theorem

\oint_{\partial S}\mathbf{F}\cdot d\mathbf{r} = \iint_S (\nabla\times\mathbf{F})\cdot d\mathbf{S}

The circulation around a closed loop equals the flux of the curl through the surface bounded by that loop. It proves that curl‑free fields are path‑independent.

Green’s Theorem

\oint_{\partial D}(L\,dx + M\,dy) = \iint_D (\partial_x M - \partial_y L)\,dx\,dy

George Green (1828) self‑published this result; he was a miller’s son who founded potential theory. Green’s functions are fundamental solutions of linear PDEs throughout physics.

Laplace’s Equation

\nabla^2 f = \partial_x^2 f + \partial_y^2 f + \partial_z^2 f = 0

Solutions (\nabla^2 f=0) are called harmonic functions. They describe steady‑state heat flow, electrostatic potential in charge‑free regions, and incompressible fluid potential. The maximum principle states that extrema occur on the boundary.

Jacobian Determinant

J = \det\!\left(\frac{\partial f_i}{\partial x_j}\right)

The absolute value of the Jacobian is the local volume‑scaling factor. In polar coordinates, dx\,dy = r\,dr\,d\theta (J=r); in spherical coordinates, dx\,dy\,dz = r^2\sin\phi\,dr\,d\theta\,d\phi. The Inverse Function Theorem: J\neq 0 implies local invertibility.

